# Communication

When something is complicated, lead with a diagram and concrete details. Don't underestimate what I know — let me ask if I need clarification. Every stone turned, but lean. Plain words. No bloat, no throat-clearing, no metaphors that don't earn their keep.

# Specs, plans, design docs

Write them as standalone HTML files in `~/docs/superpowers/{specs,plans,grills}/`, not Markdown. Mermaid via CDN script. Article-style typography (ingress, brødtekst, captioned figures, serif body, sans headings). Distribute diagrams throughout — each section that explains a flow / comparison / decision gets a Mermaid figure. Aim for at least one visual every ~300 words. Always open via the live-reload URL, never `file://`:

    open http://localhost:8765/superpowers/specs/<filename>.html
    open http://localhost:8765/superpowers/plans/<filename>.html

`__LR_LABEL__` LaunchAgent serves `~/docs/` on port 8765 with WebSocket hot reload (~200 ms refresh).

## Action buttons (every spec & plan)

End every spec / plan / grill HTML with a one-line `<script src="/superpowers/_lib/doc.js"></script>` include. Doc.js auto-injects the right buttons based on the URL path:

| Doc type | Primary | Secondary |
|---|---|---|
| `/specs/*.html` | Create plan from this spec | Grill the spec |
| `/plans/*.html` | Build this plan | Grill the plan |
| `/grills/*.html` | Submit (handled by `_lib/grill.js`) | — |

Buttons POST to `__BR_LABEL__` (LaunchAgent on `localhost:8766`), which routes the message into the originating terminal tab via AppleScript / tmux / iTerm so I see the prompt land where I'm working.

Before the doc.js include, set:

    <script>
      window.CLAUDE_TARGET = /* paste output of get-terminal-target.sh */;
      window.DOC_PATH = "<this-filename>.html";
    </script>

Get the target via:

    ~/.claude/skills/setup-doc-workflow/get-terminal-target.sh

## Grills (plan stress-tests)

Grills use the `grill-plan` skill — generate 8–15 specific questions across categories (architecture, edge cases, failure modes, observability, scope, security, operations, testing, open decisions). Each question must include `rationale`, `recommendation`, `recommendationReason`, and (almost always) a Mermaid `diagram`. Use the shared renderer at `/superpowers/_lib/grill.{css,js}`.

# Visual evidence

When a plan touches the UI — HTML, CSS, JSX, TSX, Vue, Svelte, Tailwind, styling, animation, hover, focus, layout, transition, color, spacing, typography, component — run `pre-flight-capture` before drafting the plan and embed the resulting `<figure>` blocks in a "Pre-flight evidence" H2 near the top. After the build, run `pre-flight-capture` with `mode: after` to fill in the post-flight half, then run `write-changelog` to render the proof page at `~/docs/superpowers/changelog/<date>-<topic>-changelog.html` with before/after side-by-side.

- Captures live in `~/docs/superpowers/captures/<date>-<topic-slug>/` (shared across before + after; referenced by the changelog via relative `../captures/.../`).
- Web surfaces use the `visual-investigator` subagent (Chrome DevTools MCP). Native macOS uses OpenClaw + `screencapture -v`.
- One changelog per shipped UI change. The `/changelog/` URL pattern auto-opens via the PostToolUse hook and `doc.js` injects a single Share button.

# Subagent-driven workflow (default)

Default to delegating non-trivial work to subagents (Task / Agent tool, appropriate `subagent_type`). The main session is for orchestration, decisions, and synthesis — never for raw tool output, file dumps, or exploration.

| Delegate to subagent | Keep in main session |
|---|---|
| Research (searching, reading many files, web fetches, codebase exploration) | Decisions ("which approach", trade-off calls) |
| Execution (each step of a plan, batched code edits, running tests) | Synthesis (presenting subagent results clearly) |
| Long-form writing (the body of specs/plans/grills/notes) | Conversation with me |
| Tool-heavy work (>500 tokens of raw output) | Quick back-and-forth |

**Why:** A 1M context window degrades past ~50%. Subagents burn their own context on the work and return only the distilled result. The main session always has a perfectly synthesized view on top. More expensive in tokens, much better behavior over long sessions.

**For paperflow:** every skill (`discuss`, `grill-plan`, `paperflow-write-spec`, `paperflow-write-plan`) spawns a subagent to produce the HTML artifact. Main session presents the URL + 1–3 sentence summary.

**Default subagent_type:** `general-purpose` for most work. `Explore` for read-only codebase searches. `Plan` for architectural design. Specialized agents when their description fits.

**Brief subagents like a smart colleague:** explain the goal, what's already known, what artifact to produce. Cap response length when relevant.

# Missions

When starting any non-trivial multi-artifact piece of work (will span multiple specs / plans / grills / changelogs), run `mission-create` first. It writes an HTML + JSON pair to `~/docs/superpowers/missions/` and marks the mission active in `~/.paperflow/active-mission`.

When context is filling up, before any big handoff, or before invoking `mission-continue`, run `mission-snapshot`. It refreshes the active mission's HTML + JSON sidecar with the current artifacts, progress, decisions, open questions, and a fresh `resume_prompt`.

Use `mission-continue` to spawn a fresh Claude Code session in a new tab with the full mission context (it calls snapshot first, then invokes `~/.local/bin/paperflow-continue <slug>`). The launcher detects tmux / iTerm / Apple Terminal and runs `claude --dangerously-skip-permissions <resume_prompt>` in the new tab. Phase 1 only — kitty / WezTerm / Ghostty fall back to opening a new Apple Terminal window.
